Scope Statement
From your WBS and Gantt Chart, estimate how much this project would cost if you were employed.  Use figures presented in class.
State in 1-2 paragraphs how you would control for quality.  What measurements would you take in order to make a case that this project was of high quality?
List the risks involved in doing this project at each step.  Accompany each with a statement about how you would mitigate risk.

In terms of the cost management:
- from what I understand we are supposed to make a spreadsheet right?
- Also, because our project doesn't require any pay (because we are doing this for "free", and we don't need other resources other than what we already own).   With that, should create a fictional "pay" ? So we have a number to work with the estimates?  Or can we include the costs of our own resources? (Perhaps school tuition, the cost of our computers, the cost of the books used for this class, etc?)
- Are we also supposed to put "effort" costs?  I.e. how much each activity would take to be done?

For the quality management:
- Are we supposed to use tangible ways to mesaure the quality of our project?
(Since is an app, perhaps things like reviews, number of downloads, amount of people actually using the product, how often it has been downloaded, etc?)

For the risk management:
- When it was said in the class lecture "More up front than a backup plan", 
did you mean that you are looking for ways in which we will try to mitigate risks regardless if the risks do actually happen or not?

HI Juliano,Good questions.For cost management, you are to make a spreadsheet with effort expended byeach person on your team and assume a $70,000 plus indirect costs per yearper person rate.  A year has 2000 hours in it (rough calculations).  Othercosts include not things you have anyway (e.g. a computer) but licenses,paper, consultants' time, etc., if any.For quality management, you have the right idea.  How will you know if youhave succeeded.  What is your quality goal and how will it be measured? (For bugs it could be calls to the help desk).For risk management, we are looking for an upfront listing of possiblerisks (e.g. a student dropping out of class) and what you will do about it. These are forward looking whether they happen or not.  Some thingsinevitably happen; you just don't know which.Does that answer it?Judy Olson
